== Roleplay <roleplay>

This section is dedicated to tips and observations from personal experience on
roleplaying and developing interesting, rewarding characters and stories. Take
these with a grain of salt — go with your gut instinct first and foremost.

=== Errata and Erratum

Arrata is naturally a game about conflict, failure, and success. The name itself
is a play on the word _errata_. Because of this, it's important to keep
roleplay at the forefront of the action and adventure — the numbers exist to
serve the story, not the other way around.

=== Quirks and Character Building

Quirks are critical to defining who and what your character is, but they
shouldn't be the only thing. Define a *Backstory* that fits into the setting and
world your character inhabits. Establish who they've met, who their family is,
and what shaped them. Work with your GM to write this story collaboratively —
the whole experience will be better for it.

When choosing Quirks, pick ones that conflict with other characters' Quirks as
well as your own. This makes your character more natural and lets you play those
hypocrisies vocally and mechanically. Take advantage of them and play them hard,
even when you know it's a terrible idea. The worst decisions often produce the
greatest stories.

=== War and Peace

When conflict arises, consult your Quirks first. Are you _Caliban_?
_Practical_? How would you solve this to benefit yourself and only yourself? How
would you solve it to help everyone?

Put these questions forward and see what _feels_ right for your character.
Discuss your options with the other players and the GM — you'll grow into the
character's shoes much faster than sitting quietly in the corner.

=== Moral Ambiguity

Good and Evil are not terms Arrata traditionally deals with. There is no
morality system, no two-dimensional chart to define a character's ideology, and
that is by design. Ideas are not static once they enter the brain. Being a
narcissist doesn't mean you burn orphanages, but it also doesn't make you a
beacon of humility. Every Quirk carries both positive and negative weight,
even if some are certainly skewed one way.

=== Evolution

Take advantage of the fact that Quirks can change. Develop a core set of
important Quirks rather than spreading thinly across a wide range of barely
used ones.

A note for GMs and players alike: offer and pursue Challenges that involve
difficult moral scenarios. Thinking not as yourself in your own mindset and
ideology, but as a different person in a different world surrounded by
circumstances beyond your experience — that is what makes roleplaying
interesting and what makes it such a powerful way to tell stories. It is more
than reading; it is writing and living in those stories.

=== Confidence and Curiosity

Roleplaying is difficult. It can be awkward and embarrassing. People will
perceive things differently and demand you change. This is where one rule
should be made clear:

#align(center)[*Do not let anyone define who or what you're playing other than yourself and the dice.*]

It's a simple idea and one easily forgotten when someone chants "_Kick him down
the stairs!_" in glee. The first step to getting comfortable with roleplaying
is acknowledging that you cannot let others write your story for you.

After that, it gets easier. Try an accent. Augment your language to match the
character. Use a point of view that fits: if your character is snobbish and
self-absorbed, speak in the first person and be pejorative; if they are quiet
and withdrawn, use the third person and a more reserved diction. Portraying a
character is not only about how they act in the game — it is about how they
think and communicate.

=== Earning Intuition

Playing a Quirk well is subjective, but the foremost rule of thumb is
_conviction_. Believe your Quirks are positive when you play them — unless the
Quirk generally disagrees with that interpretation. A _Degenerate_ does not
inherently see their ideology as regressive, and neither should you when
playing them. Express these Quirks freely; that is what Arrata is built for.

In the same vein, choose a Quirk with which your character is keenly aware
there is a problem. Act on it with disdain and apologetic vigour. There are
parts of people that they wish were different — this is a chance to play that
uncomfortable reality out.

Playing Quirks in enduring, repulsive, or altogether inspiring ways is solid
grounds for an Intuition point. On the other hand, acting on a Quirk once per
session — cleaning a jacket because you have the _Anal_ quirk and doing nothing
else — then demanding Intuition, is neither compelling nor strong roleplaying.

